## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — it spawns a thread, waits for a deadline, then forcibly aborts. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op.

### What's Wrong on .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — timeout never works |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`), no-op on modern .NET |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource with built-in timeout
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout; throws on cancellation
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The above abandons the task but **doesn't stop it** — cooperative cancellation requires the work to check a token. Pass one through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then cooperate:

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the work runs until it hits a checkpoint. CPU-bound code without `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` calls will run to completion. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls a library that can't accept a token, the task is abandoned but the thread keeps running. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+ only** | This API doesn't exist on .NET Framework. Fine for your .NET 8 target. |

### Async version (preferred if callers can be async)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

This avoids blocking a thread pool thread with `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` entirely.
